  <title>
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">Emergency WASH Response for Returnees in Aleppo</narrative>
  </title>
  <description type="2">
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">On the evening of Monday 12 December, the government forces and its allies were in control of 99 per cent of Aleppo&#x2019;s formerly rebel-held territory. Since then, more than 121,350 people originally from east Aleppo city have been officially registered in different locations. Of those, 65,345 remained or re-registered in east Aleppo, 50,929 are registered as sheltering in west Aleppo, and 5,077 remain in the Jibreen collective shelter. Since 14 January 2017, an estimated 1.8 million people in Aleppo city and rural eastern Aleppo have been cut off from the main source of water supply. The humanitarian situation is dire. The scale of destruction in massive, and the needs for basic services, shelter, protection and rehabilitation of infrastructure are widespread in both urban and rural areas. 

This project will complement and will give continuity to an emergency intervention that AAH is ready to launch (OCHA funded project together with GAC of Canada funded project). Currently, AAH has the capacity, funding  and is ready to install 70 community water tanks (5,000 m3 capacity), distribute 15,000 jerry cans (which 10,000 are small capacity 10liters for ease of carrying) and cover the immediate water needs of 23,500 people (estimated number of returnees at the time of writing) for 25 days. Considering the increasing number of returnees, the current cut off from Aleppo&#x2019;s main source of water, and the extensive damage and demolition of the public network, it is crucial to reinstate continuous access to safe drinking water through  Installation of 30 water tanks, distribution of 500 m3 of safe water on daily basis during 60 days.  In addition, commencing the rehabilitation of the water and sanitation systems is clearly a key in reinstating health and dignity for Aleppo&#x2019;s population.

Target populations will be 25,000 returnees in Bustar Al Qaser, Fardos, Kallaseh, and Karm El&#x2019;d&#x2019;da. The project integrates gender equality considerations in all its components, and places a specific focus on addressing the needs of women, boys and girls.</narrative>
  </description>
